.SH NAME
Net::Nostr::Negentropy \- NIP\-77 negentropy set reconciliation
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&    use Net::Nostr::Negentropy;
\&
\&    # Client side
\&    my $client = Net::Nostr::Negentropy\->new;
\&    $client\->add_item(1000, \*(Aq01\*(Aq x 32);
\&    $client\->add_item(2000, \*(Aq02\*(Aq x 32);
\&    $client\->seal;
\&
\&    my $q = $client\->initiate;
\&    # Send $q in NEG\-OPEN message
\&
\&    # Server side
\&    my $server = Net::Nostr::Negentropy\->new;
\&    $server\->add_item(1000, \*(Aq01\*(Aq x 32);
\&    $server\->add_item(3000, \*(Aq03\*(Aq x 32);
\&    $server\->seal;
\&
\&    my ($response, $s_have, $s_need) = $server\->reconcile($q);
\&    # Send $response in NEG\-MSG
\&
\&    # Client processes response
\&    my ($next, $c_have, $c_need) = $client\->reconcile($response);
\&    # $c_have = [\*(Aq02\*(Aq x 32]   \-\- client has, server doesn\*(Aqt
\&    # $c_need = [\*(Aq03\*(Aq x 32]   \-\- server has, client doesn\*(Aqt
\&    # If $next is defined, send as NEG\-MSG and continue
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Implements the Negentropy set reconciliation protocol as specified in
NIP\-77. This protocol efficiently determines the symmetric difference
between two sets of events by exchanging fingerprints and progressively
narrowing mismatched ranges.
.PP
The protocol uses a binary message format with varint encoding,
range\-based fingerprints (SHA\-256 of modular ID sums), and ID lists.
Messages are hex\-encoded for transmission over the Nostr WebSocket
protocol.
.PP
Typical flow:
.IP "1. Both sides create a Negentropy instance, add their local events via ""add_item"", and call ""seal""." 4
.IX Item "1. Both sides create a Negentropy instance, add their local events via ""add_item"", and call ""seal""."
.PD 0
.IP "2. The client (initiator) calls ""initiate"" to produce the initial message." 4
.IX Item "2. The client (initiator) calls ""initiate"" to produce the initial message."
.IP "3. The server calls ""reconcile"" with the client\*(Aqs message and returns a response." 4
.IX Item "3. The server calls ""reconcile"" with the client's message and returns a response."
.ie n .IP "4. The client calls ""reconcile"" with the server\*(Aqs response. If the return message is ""undef"", the protocol is complete. Otherwise, send the message and repeat from step 3." 4
.el .IP "4. The client calls ""reconcile"" with the server\*(Aqs response. If the return message is \f(CWundef\fR, the protocol is complete. Otherwise, send the message and repeat from step 3." 4
.IX Item "4. The client calls ""reconcile"" with the server's response. If the return message is undef, the protocol is complete. Otherwise, send the message and repeat from step 3."
.PD
.PP
After reconciliation, the client knows which IDs it has that the
server lacks (\f(CW\*(C`have\*(C'\fR) and which IDs the server has that it lacks
(\f(CW\*(C`need\*(C'\fR). It can then use \f(CW\*(C`EVENT\*(C'\fR to upload and \f(CW\*(C`REQ\*(C'\fR to download.
.SH CONSTRUCTOR
.IX Header "CONSTRUCTOR"
.SS new
.IX Subsection "new"
.Vb 2
\&    my $ne = Net::Nostr::Negentropy\->new;
\&    my $ne = Net::Nostr::Negentropy\->new(frame_size_limit => 4096);
.Ve
.PP
Creates a new Negentropy instance. Croaks on unknown arguments.
.PP
Options:
.ie n .IP """frame_size_limit"" \-\- maximum byte size for encoded protocol messages. Defaults to 0 (unlimited)." 4
.el .IP "\f(CWframe_size_limit\fR \-\- maximum byte size for encoded protocol messages. Defaults to \f(CW0\fR (unlimited)." 4
.IX Item "frame_size_limit -- maximum byte size for encoded protocol messages. Defaults to 0 (unlimited)."
.SH METHODS
.IX Header "METHODS"
.SS add_item
.IX Subsection "add_item"
.Vb 1
\&    $ne\->add_item($timestamp, $id_hex);
.Ve
.PP
Adds an event to the local set. \f(CW$timestamp\fR must be a non\-negative
integer (the event\*(Aqs \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR). The maximum uint64 value
(\f(CW\*(C`2**64 \- 1\*(C'\fR) is reserved as the protocol\*(Aqs infinity timestamp and
is rejected. \f(CW$id_hex\fR must be a 64\-character lowercase hex string
(the event ID). Croaks if called after "seal".
.SS seal
.IX Subsection "seal"
.Vb 1
\&    $ne\->seal;
.Ve
.PP
Sorts the items and finalizes the set. Must be called before
"initiate" or "reconcile". After sealing, "add_item" is no
longer allowed.
.SS initiate
.IX Subsection "initiate"
.Vb 1
\&    my $hex_msg = $ne\->initiate;
.Ve
.PP
Creates the initial reconciliation message. Returns a hex\-encoded
binary message string. This marks the instance as the initiator
(client side). Croaks if not sealed.
.SS reconcile
.IX Subsection "reconcile"
.Vb 1
\&    my ($hex_response, $have_ids, $need_ids) = $ne\->reconcile($hex_msg);
.Ve
.PP
Processes a reconciliation message from the other side. Returns:
.ie n .IP "$hex_response \-\- the response message (hex string), or ""undef"" if the protocol is complete" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$hex_response\fR \-\- the response message (hex string), or \f(CWundef\fR if the protocol is complete" 4
.IX Item "$hex_response -- the response message (hex string), or undef if the protocol is complete"
.PD 0
.ie n .IP "$have_ids \-\- arrayref of hex ID strings that we have and they don\*(Aqt" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$have_ids\fR \-\- arrayref of hex ID strings that we have and they don\*(Aqt" 4
.IX Item "$have_ids -- arrayref of hex ID strings that we have and they don't"
.ie n .IP "$need_ids \-\- arrayref of hex ID strings that they have and we don\*(Aqt" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$need_ids\fR \-\- arrayref of hex ID strings that they have and we don\*(Aqt" 4
.IX Item "$need_ids -- arrayref of hex ID strings that they have and we don't"
.PD
.PP
Croaks if not sealed.
